{"title_page": "Hamantash", "text_new": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Hamantash\n| image            = Mohn hamantaschen.jpg\n| caption          = Mohn (poppyseed) hamantash.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cookie]] or [[pastry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = \n| variations       = Filling: traditionally [[poppy seed]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = \n}}\n\nA '''hamantash''' (pl. '''''hamantashen'''''; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9}} ''homentash'', pl. {{lang|yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df}} ''homentashn'', literally 'Haman pockets') is an [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine|Ashkenazi Jewish]] triangular filled-pocket [[cookie]], usually associated with the [[Jewish]] holiday of [[Purim]]. The name refers to [[Haman]], the villain in the Purim story. In Hebrew, hamantashen are known as {{lang|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}, '''''oznei Haman''''', literally 'Haman's ears'.\n\nThe shape is achieved by folding in the sides of a circular piece of dough similar to a [[shortbread]], with a filling placed in the center.  Hamantashen are made with many different fillings, which are traditionally sweet (although savory varieties have become popular as well), including [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]] ([[poppy seed]], the oldest and most traditional variety), [[lekvar]] ([[prune]] jam), nut, [[Date (fruit)|date]], [[apricot]], [[raspberry]], [[raisins]], [[apple]], vanilla [[pastry cream]] with [[chocolate chips]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads |publisher=Artisan Books}}</ref> [[cherry]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[chocolate]], [[dulce de leche]], [[halva]], or even [[caramel]] or [[cheese]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |title=Epi Log: The latest in Food News, the Culinary Arts & Cooking<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-03-25 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630123404/http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |archive-date=2012-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their formation varies from hard similar to a [[shortbread]] to soft doughy casings.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Plate4Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Four hamantashen: (clockwise from top left) chocolate, poppy seed, blueberry, and cherry.]]\nIn Yiddish, the word ''homentash'' is singular, while ''homentashen'' is the plural form. However, ''hamantashen'' is the more common word form among English speakers, even when referring to a single pastry (for example, \"I ate a poppy seed hamantashen\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdjewishworld.com/2013/02/22/all-about-hamantaschen/|title=All about hamantaschen|last=Rosenthal|first=Leonard|date=22 February 2013|website=[[San Diego Jewish World]]|publisher=Donald H. & Nancy E. Harrison|access-date=28 September 2016|quote=...that does not stop people from using the plural even when they are referring to the singular...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learnreligions.com/what-are-hamantaschen-2076476|title=Why Do Jews Eat Hamentaschen During Purim?|last=Pelaia|first=Ariela|website=Learn Religions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Name and symbolism==\n''Hamantash'' is also spelled ''hamentasch'', ''homentash'', ''homentasch'', ''homentaschan'', or even ''(h)umentash''. The name ''hamantash'' is commonly viewed as a reference to [[Haman (Bible)|Haman]], the villain of [[Purim]], as described in the [[Book of Esther]]. The pastries are supposed to symbolize the defeated enemy of the Jewish people.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=613&letter=P&search=hamantaschen ''Purim, ''Jewish Encyclopedia, 1906], 'In this connection it may be mentioned that for the celebration of Purim there developed among the Jews a special kind of baking. Cakes were shaped into certain forms and were given names having some symbolic bearing on the historical events of Purim. Thus the Jews of Germany eat \"Hamantaschen\" and \"Hamanohren\" (in Italy, \"orrechi d'Aman\"), \"Kreppchen,\" \"Kindchen,\" etc.'</ref> The word ''tash'' means \"pouch\" or \"pocket\" in Yiddish, and thus may refer to ''Haman's pockets'', symbolizing the money that Haman offered to Ahasuerus in exchange for permission to destroy the Jews. In Hebrew, ''tash'' means \"weaken\", and the hamantash may celebrate the weakening of Haman and the hope that God will weaken all of the enemies of the Jews.<ref name=\"shurpin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chabad.org/holidays/purim/article_cdo/aid/2872815/jewish/The-History-and-Meaning-of-Hamantaschen.htm |title=The History and Meaning of Hamantaschen |last=Shurpin |first=Yehuda |website=Chabad.org  |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Another possible source of the name is a [[folk etymology]]: the Yiddish word \u05de\u05d0\u05b8\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df (''montashn'') for a traditional delicacy, literally meaning \"poppyseed pouch\",<ref>[http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm MyJewishLearning.com - Holidays: Purim Foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302140457/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm |date=2007-03-02 }}</ref> was transformed to ''hamantaschen'', likely by association with Haman or inclusion of the Hebrew article {{transl|he|ha-}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d4}}).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} In [[Israel]], hamantaschen are called ''oznei Haman'' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}), [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] for \"Haman's ears\" in reference to their defeated enemy's ears.\n\nThe reason for the three-sided shape is uncertain. There is an old legend that Haman wore a three-cornered hat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewinsky |first=Yom Tov |date=1958 |title=Sefer Hamoadim |pages=154|url=http://chabadlibrarybooks.com/pdfpager.aspx?req=41737&st=&pgnum=169 |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, the [[Midrash]] says that when Haman recognized the merit of the [[Patriarchs (Bible)|Three Patriarchs]], his strength immediately weakened.<ref name=\"shurpin\"/> ''[[Naked Archaeologist]]'' documentarian [[Simcha Jacobovici]] has shown the resemblance of hamantaschen to dice from the ancient Babylonian [[Royal Game of Ur]], thus suggesting that the pastries are meant to symbolize the pyramidal shape of the dice cast by Haman in determining the day of destruction for the Jews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |title=Filmmaker unearths mystery |last1=Gordon |first1=Dave |date=April 8, 2011 |website=Jewish Independent |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314133528/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |archivedate=March 14, 2014 }}</ref> A simpler explanation is that the shape derives from traditional Jewish baking techniques in Central Europe for folding dough so as to form a pouch around a filling, also common for making dumplings.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} It has also been suggested that the shape is a representation of female reproductive organs, and that the poppy-seed filling is a fertility symbol.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schnur |first1=Susan |title=From Prenistoric Cave Art To Your Cookie Pan: Tracing The Hamantasch Herstory |journal=Lilith |date=Spring 1998 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=22-4 |url=https://lilith.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/v23i01_Spring_1998-08.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Arielle |title=Yes, There\u2019s a Reason Hamantaschen Look Like Vaginas |url=https://www.heyalma.com/yes-theres-a-reason-hamantaschen-look-like-vaginas/ |website=Alma |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sweet fillings==\nSweet hamantaschen fillings range from the traditional such as [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]]/poppy seed, [[prune|lekvar]]/prune, [[apricot jam]], and also date which is especially popular in Israel.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref> \n\n===Prune===\nPrune hamantaschen was invented in 1731 by David Brandeis of [[Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Jung-Bunzlau]], [[Bohemia]]. The daughter of a Christian bookbinder purchased from Brandeis povidl (plum jam) which she claimed had made her family ill; as her father coincidentally died a few days after eating it. The [[burgomaster]] of the city ordered the closure of Brandeis' store and imprisoned him, his wife, and son for selling poisonous food to Christians. Investigations by municipal authorities and the court of appeal in Prague revealed that the bookbinder had died of [[Tuberculosis|consumption]] and the charges were dismissed. Brandeis wrote a scroll which he called ''Shir HaMa'alot l'David'' (\"A [[Song of Ascents]] to David\"), to be read on 10 Adar, accompanied by a festive meal. He was freed from prison four days before Purim after the charges against him were proven to be false, and in celebration of his release, Jews from his city celebrated with povidl or plum hamantaschen.\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sacharin |first1=Emily |title=A Purim Classic: Sugar Cookie Hamantaschen |url=https://www.poppyandprune.com/2018/02/12/purim-classic-sugar-cookie-hamantaschen/ |website=Poppy and Prune |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Purims, Special |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204004/http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 March 2016 |website=Jewish Encyclopedia |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips===\n\n[[File:Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Hamantash filled with vanilla pastry cream and chocolate chips prior to baking.]]\n\nIsraeli baker Uri Scheft offers hamantaschen filled with a vanilla [[custard|pastry cream]] and chocolate chips at Lehamim/Breads Bakery, his bakeries in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]]. A recipe for this filling is also featured in Scheft's cookbook.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n==Savory fillings==\nSavory hamantaschen fillings have emerged in recent years, and their popularity has grown and are commonly prepared at home but can also be found in various Jewish bakeries and restaurants serving Jewish cuisine. Savory varieties may have fillings such as [[pizza]], spinach and feta, lamb, potato, or cheese, and are often somewhat similar to other [[Jewish cuisine|Jewish]] pastries such as the [[knish]], [[bourekas]], and sambusak.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Preparation==\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Soldiers Volunteer for Purim with Bereaved Families of Fallen Soldiers (1).jpg|thumb|right|Volunteers in Israel preparing hamantaschen for Purim with the children of fallen soldiers.]]\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy seed hamantaschen prior to baking.]]\n\nSweet hamantaschen are typically made with a dough containing butter or, less-commmonly a [[pareve]] dough containing oil. Depending on the ingredients used in the dough, the consistency of the finished hamantaschen can range from dry and crumbly like to a [[shortbread]], to soft and cakey like a [[black and white cookie]], to firm and crisp like a butter cookie. The dough is generally prepared with flour, eggs, sugar, butter (or margarine or cooking oil), and a flavoring such as vanilla (or sometimes [[cocoa]], [[rose water]], or [[orange blossom water]] may be used); sometimes milk is used in the dough, and sometimes a leavener such as baking powder or baking soda is added as well. The dough is then mixed gently so as to incorporate all the ingredients together but not make the dough tough and give the hamantaschen an inferior texture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen Purim Dresden (1).JPG|thumb|right|Hamantaschen served at a Purim party in Dresden that have been dusted with powdered sugar.]]\n\nThe dough is allowed to rest in the refrigerator and is then removed and rolled out to a thickness of between 1/8 and 1/4 of an inch; rounds of dough are stamped out and are often brushed with an [[egg wash]] to encourage sealing prior to the addition of the filling. The most popular filling is [[poppyseed]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>, but apricot, prune, strawberry, raspberry, chocolate, [[peanut butter and jelly]], and others are also common. The bottom and the top two corners of the dough are folded inward but do not fully enclose the filling, allowing it to remain visible. Sometimes hamantaschen may be frozen for a short period of time after shaping in order to prevent leakage of the filling. Then they are baked in an oven at medium heat for a short duration of time. Sometimes after baking hamantaschen may be dusted with [[confectioner's sugar]], dipped in [[melted chocolate]], or topped with [[sprinkles]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nathan |first1=Joan |title=The Jewish Holiday Cookbook}}</ref>\n\nSavory hamantaschen are prepared in much the same way as sweet hamantaschen, with the exception of the fillings; and they are generally made with a different dough, such one similar to a [[pie]] crust or [[puff pastry]], or a modified sweet hamantaschen dough containing less sugar.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Hamantash by country==\n\n\n===Israel===\n\n[[File:Purim In Mahne Yehuda.jpg|thumb|right|Bakers selling hamantaschen as part of Purim celebrations at [[Machne Yehuda]] in [[Jerusalem, Israel]].]]\n\n{{blockquote|\"In recent years, Israeli bakeries have increasingly offered gourmet versions of the three-cornered cookie \u2014 marzipan, say, or gluten-free varieties \u2014 alongside the classics, like poppyseed. The change reflects the growing sophistication of Israel\u2019s culinary scene, which is focused on updating traditional dishes and fusing them with cuisines from around the world.\"|Andrew Tobin|[[The Times of Israel]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Logistics Branch Celebrates Purim (1).jpg|thumb|right|Hamantaschen baked by members of the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] [[Logistics Corps]] as part of a baking competition hosted by a winner of the [[Masterchef Israel]] television series.]]\nHamantaschen are known as ''\"oznei haman\"'' in Israel, and are the most popular cookie sold at bakeries across Israel in the weeks leading up to the celebration of Purim each year, with both large chains and small independent bakeries offering many different varieties. As in the [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]], [[Poppy seed filling|poppyseed]] remains the most-popular filling, with chocolate in second, and date filling coming in third in popularity. Jam is not nearly as common a filling as in America.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref> \n\nEach year bakeries offer new, innovative flavors of hamantaschen. Roladin, a popular Israeli bakery chain offers oznei haman with fillings such as goat cheese and onion jam, [[amaretto]]-pistachio-marzipan, and [[triple-sec]] [[cheesecake]], among others. In 2017, Roladin announced that they were launching a dozen new flavors as well as reinvented versions of the more traditional fillings, and projected that they would sell over 2 million oznei haman during the Purim season. Lehamim Bakery, which has locations in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]] offers fillings such as [[sweet potato]] and feta, [[charoset]], vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips, apple, [[marzipan]], and others. Oren Becker, an Israeli pastry chef has started making gluten free, vegan low or no-sugar, and low fat hamantaschen, and has said his personal favorite is made with a whole grain dough and filled with [[goji berries]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latke\u2013Hamantash Debate]]\n* [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Israeli cuisine]]\n* [[American Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Culture of Israel]]\n* [[Ma'amoul]]- a similar [[Mizrahi Jewish cuisine|Mizrahi Jewish]] filled cookie traditionally served for [[Purim]]\n* [[Jam tart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Purim Footer}}\n{{Jewish baked goods}}\n{{pastries}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Jewish cookies]]\n[[Category:Israeli pastries]]\n[[Category:Pastries with poppy seeds]]\n[[Category:Purim foods]]\n[[Category:Yiddish words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Hamantash\n| image            = Mohn hamantaschen.jpg\n| caption          = Mohn (poppyseed) hamantash.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cookie]] or [[pastry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = \n| variations       = Filling: traditionally [[poppy seed]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = \n}}\n\nA '''hamantash''' (pl. '''''hamantashen'''''; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9}} ''homentash'', pl. {{lang|yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df}} ''homentashn'', literally 'Haman pockets') is an [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine|Ashkenazi Jewish]] triangular filled-pocket [[cookie]], usually associated with the [[Jewish]] holiday of [[Purim]]. The name refers to [[Haman]], the villain in the Purim story. In Hebrew, hamantashen are known as {{lang|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}, '''''oznei Haman''''', literally 'Haman's ears'.\n\nThe shape is achieved by folding in the sides of a circular piece of dough similar to a [[shortbread]], with a filling placed in the center.  Hamantashen are made with many different fillings, which are traditionally sweet (although savory varieties have become popular as well), including [[mohn]] ([[poppy seed]], the oldest and most traditional variety), [[lekvar]] ([[prune]] jam), nut, [[Date (fruit)|date]], [[apricot]], [[raspberry]], [[raisins]], [[apple]], vanilla [[pastry cream]] with [[chocolate chips]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads |publisher=Artisan Books}}</ref> [[cherry]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[chocolate]], [[dulce de leche]], [[halva]], or even [[caramel]] or [[cheese]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |title=Epi Log: The latest in Food News, the Culinary Arts & Cooking<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-03-25 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630123404/http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |archive-date=2012-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their formation varies from hard similar to a [[shortbread]] to soft doughy casings.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Plate4Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Four hamantashen: (clockwise from top left) chocolate, poppy seed, blueberry, and cherry.]]\nIn Yiddish, the word ''homentash'' is singular, while ''homentashen'' is the plural form. However, ''hamantashen'' is the more common word form among English speakers, even when referring to a single pastry (for example, \"I ate a poppy seed hamantashen\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdjewishworld.com/2013/02/22/all-about-hamantaschen/|title=All about hamantaschen|last=Rosenthal|first=Leonard|date=22 February 2013|website=[[San Diego Jewish World]]|publisher=Donald H. & Nancy E. Harrison|access-date=28 September 2016|quote=...that does not stop people from using the plural even when they are referring to the singular...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learnreligions.com/what-are-hamantaschen-2076476|title=Why Do Jews Eat Hamentaschen During Purim?|last=Pelaia|first=Ariela|website=Learn Religions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Name and symbolism==\n''Hamantash'' is also spelled ''hamentasch'', ''homentash'', ''homentasch'', ''homentaschan'', or even ''(h)umentash''. The name ''hamantash'' is commonly viewed as a reference to [[Haman (Bible)|Haman]], the villain of [[Purim]], as described in the [[Book of Esther]]. The pastries are supposed to symbolize the defeated enemy of the Jewish people.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=613&letter=P&search=hamantaschen ''Purim, ''Jewish Encyclopedia, 1906], 'In this connection it may be mentioned that for the celebration of Purim there developed among the Jews a special kind of baking. Cakes were shaped into certain forms and were given names having some symbolic bearing on the historical events of Purim. Thus the Jews of Germany eat \"Hamantaschen\" and \"Hamanohren\" (in Italy, \"orrechi d'Aman\"), \"Kreppchen,\" \"Kindchen,\" etc.'</ref> The word ''tash'' means \"pouch\" or \"pocket\" in Yiddish, and thus may refer to ''Haman's pockets'', symbolizing the money that Haman offered to Ahasuerus in exchange for permission to destroy the Jews. In Hebrew, ''tash'' means \"weaken\", and the hamantash may celebrate the weakening of Haman and the hope that God will weaken all of the enemies of the Jews.<ref name=\"shurpin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chabad.org/holidays/purim/article_cdo/aid/2872815/jewish/The-History-and-Meaning-of-Hamantaschen.htm |title=The History and Meaning of Hamantaschen |last=Shurpin |first=Yehuda |website=Chabad.org  |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Another possible source of the name is a [[folk etymology]]: the Yiddish word \u05de\u05d0\u05b8\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df (''montashn'') for a traditional delicacy, literally meaning \"poppyseed pouch\",<ref>[http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm MyJewishLearning.com - Holidays: Purim Foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302140457/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm |date=2007-03-02 }}</ref> was transformed to ''hamantaschen'', likely by association with Haman or inclusion of the Hebrew article {{transl|he|ha-}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d4}}).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} In [[Israel]], hamantaschen are called ''oznei Haman'' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}), [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] for \"Haman's ears\" in reference to their defeated enemy's ears.\n\nThe reason for the three-sided shape is uncertain. There is an old legend that Haman wore a three-cornered hat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewinsky |first=Yom Tov |date=1958 |title=Sefer Hamoadim |pages=154|url=http://chabadlibrarybooks.com/pdfpager.aspx?req=41737&st=&pgnum=169 |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, the [[Midrash]] says that when Haman recognized the merit of the [[Patriarchs (Bible)|Three Patriarchs]], his strength immediately weakened.<ref name=\"shurpin\"/> ''[[Naked Archaeologist]]'' documentarian [[Simcha Jacobovici]] has shown the resemblance of hamantaschen to dice from the ancient Babylonian [[Royal Game of Ur]], thus suggesting that the pastries are meant to symbolize the pyramidal shape of the dice cast by Haman in determining the day of destruction for the Jews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |title=Filmmaker unearths mystery |last1=Gordon |first1=Dave |date=April 8, 2011 |website=Jewish Independent |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314133528/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |archivedate=March 14, 2014 }}</ref> A simpler explanation is that the shape derives from traditional Jewish baking techniques in Central Europe for folding dough so as to form a pouch around a filling, also common for making dumplings.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} It has also been suggested that the shape is a representation of female reproductive organs, and that the poppy-seed filling is a fertility symbol.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schnur |first1=Susan |title=From Prenistoric Cave Art To Your Cookie Pan: Tracing The Hamantasch Herstory |journal=Lilith |date=Spring 1998 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=22-4 |url=https://lilith.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/v23i01_Spring_1998-08.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Arielle |title=Yes, There\u2019s a Reason Hamantaschen Look Like Vaginas |url=https://www.heyalma.com/yes-theres-a-reason-hamantaschen-look-like-vaginas/ |website=Alma |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sweet fillings==\nSweet hamantaschen fillings range from the traditional such as [[mohn]]/poppy seed, [[prune|lekvar]]/prune, [[apricot jam]], and also date which is especially popular in Israel.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref> \n\n===Prune===\nPrune hamantaschen was invented in 1731 by David Brandeis of [[Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Jung-Bunzlau]], [[Bohemia]]. The daughter of a Christian bookbinder purchased from Brandeis povidl (plum jam) which she claimed had made her family ill; as her father coincidentally died a few days after eating it. The [[burgomaster]] of the city ordered the closure of Brandeis' store and imprisoned him, his wife, and son for selling poisonous food to Christians. Investigations by municipal authorities and the court of appeal in Prague revealed that the bookbinder had died of [[Tuberculosis|consumption]] and the charges were dismissed. Brandeis wrote a scroll which he called ''Shir HaMa'alot l'David'' (\"A [[Song of Ascents]] to David\"), to be read on 10 Adar, accompanied by a festive meal. He was freed from prison four days before Purim after the charges against him were proven to be false, and in celebration of his release, Jews from his city celebrated with povidl or plum hamantaschen.\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sacharin |first1=Emily |title=A Purim Classic: Sugar Cookie Hamantaschen |url=https://www.poppyandprune.com/2018/02/12/purim-classic-sugar-cookie-hamantaschen/ |website=Poppy and Prune |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Purims, Special |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204004/http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 March 2016 |website=Jewish Encyclopedia |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips===\n\n[[File:Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Hamantash filled with vanilla pastry cream and chocolate chips prior to baking.]]\n\nIsraeli baker Uri Scheft offers hamantaschen filled with a vanilla [[custard|pastry cream]] and chocolate chips at Lehamim/Breads Bakery, his bakeries in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]]. A recipe for this filling is also featured in Scheft's cookbook.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n==Savory fillings==\nSavory hamantaschen fillings have emerged in recent years, and their popularity has grown and are commonly prepared at home but can also be found in various Jewish bakeries and restaurants serving Jewish cuisine. Savory varieties may have fillings such as [[pizza]], spinach and feta, lamb, potato, or cheese, and are often somewhat similar to other [[Jewish cuisine|Jewish]] pastries such as the [[knish]], [[bourekas]], and sambusak.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Preparation==\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Soldiers Volunteer for Purim with Bereaved Families of Fallen Soldiers (1).jpg|thumb|right|Volunteers in Israel preparing hamantaschen for Purim with the children of fallen soldiers.]]\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy seed hamantaschen prior to baking.]]\n\nSweet hamantaschen are typically made with a dough containing butter or, less-commmonly a [[pareve]] dough containing oil. Depending on the ingredients used in the dough, the consistency of the finished hamantaschen can range from dry and crumbly like to a [[shortbread]], to soft and cakey like a [[black and white cookie]], to firm and crisp like a butter cookie. The dough is generally prepared with flour, eggs, sugar, butter (or margarine or cooking oil), and a flavoring such as vanilla (or sometimes [[cocoa]], [[rose water]], or [[orange blossom water]] may be used); sometimes milk is used in the dough, and sometimes a leavener such as baking powder or baking soda is added as well. The dough is then mixed gently so as to incorporate all the ingredients together but not make the dough tough and give the hamantaschen an inferior texture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen Purim Dresden (1).JPG|thumb|right|Hamantaschen served at a Purim party in Dresden that have been dusted with powdered sugar.]]\n\nThe dough is allowed to rest in the refrigerator and is then removed and rolled out to a thickness of between 1/8 and 1/4 of an inch; rounds of dough are stamped out and are often brushed with an [[egg wash]] to encourage sealing prior to the addition of the filling. The most popular filling is [[poppyseed]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>, but apricot, prune, strawberry, raspberry, chocolate, [[peanut butter and jelly]], and others are also common. The bottom and the top two corners of the dough are folded inward but do not fully enclose the filling, allowing it to remain visible. Sometimes hamantaschen may be frozen for a short period of time after shaping in order to prevent leakage of the filling. Then they are baked in an oven at medium heat for a short duration of time. Sometimes after baking hamantaschen may be dusted with [[confectioner's sugar]], dipped in [[melted chocolate]], or topped with [[sprinkles]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nathan |first1=Joan |title=The Jewish Holiday Cookbook}}</ref>\n\nSavory hamantaschen are prepared in much the same way as sweet hamantaschen, with the exception of the fillings; and they are generally made with a different dough, such one similar to a [[pie]] crust or [[puff pastry]], or a modified sweet hamantaschen dough containing less sugar.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Hamantash by country==\n\n\n===Israel===\n\n[[File:Purim In Mahne Yehuda.jpg|thumb|right|Bakers selling hamantaschen as part of Purim celebrations at [[Machne Yehuda]] in [[Jerusalem, Israel]].]]\n\n{{blockquote|\"In recent years, Israeli bakeries have increasingly offered gourmet versions of the three-cornered cookie \u2014 marzipan, say, or gluten-free varieties \u2014 alongside the classics, like poppyseed. The change reflects the growing sophistication of Israel\u2019s culinary scene, which is focused on updating traditional dishes and fusing them with cuisines from around the world.\"|Andrew Tobin|[[The Times of Israel]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Logistics Branch Celebrates Purim (1).jpg|thumb|right|Hamantaschen baked by members of the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] [[Logistics Corps]] as part of a baking competition hosted by a winner of the [[Masterchef Israel]] television series.]]\nHamantaschen are known as ''\"oznei haman\"'' in Israel, and are the most popular cookie sold at bakeries across Israel in the weeks leading up to the celebration of Purim each year, with both large chains and small independent bakeries offering many different varieties. As in the [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]], [[mohn|poppyseed]] remains the most-popular filling, with chocolate in second, and date filling coming in third in popularity. Jam is not nearly as common a filling as in America.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref> \n\nEach year bakeries offer new, innovative flavors of hamantaschen. Roladin, a popular Israeli bakery chain offers oznei haman with fillings such as goat cheese and onion jam, [[amaretto]]-pistachio-marzipan, and [[triple-sec]] [[cheesecake]], among others. In 2017, Roladin announced that they were launching a dozen new flavors as well as reinvented versions of the more traditional fillings, and projected that they would sell over 2 million oznei haman during the Purim season. Lehamim Bakery, which has locations in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]] offers fillings such as [[sweet potato]] and feta, [[charoset]], vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips, apple, [[marzipan]], and others. Oren Becker, an Israeli pastry chef has started making gluten free, vegan low or no-sugar, and low fat hamantaschen, and has said his personal favorite is made with a whole grain dough and filled with [[goji berries]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latke\u2013Hamantash Debate]]\n* [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Israeli cuisine]]\n* [[American Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Culture of Israel]]\n* [[Ma'amoul]]- a similar [[Mizrahi Jewish cuisine|Mizrahi Jewish]] filled cookie traditionally served for [[Purim]]\n* [[Jam tart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Purim Footer}}\n{{Jewish baked goods}}\n{{pastries}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Jewish cookies]]\n[[Category:Israeli pastries]]\n[[Category:Pastries with poppy seeds]]\n[[Category:Purim foods]]\n[[Category:Yiddish words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMohn(link changed toPoppy seed filling; link changed toPoppy seed filling; link changed toPoppy seed filling) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamantash"}
{"title_page": "G\u00e9raldine Mackie", "text_new": "{{short description|American speed skater}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = G\u00e9raldine Mackie\n| nickname = \u201cJerry\u201d Mackie<ref name=archive.macleans />\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = Canada\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = \n|medaltemplates=\n\n}}\n'''G\u00e9raldine Mackie''' was a female [[Canada|Canadian]] [[speed skater]]. She lived in [[Toronto]], Canada.<ref name=archive.macleans>[https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1929/3/1/speed-is-their-game]</ref>\n\nShe competed in all the three women's [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|speed skating events at the 1932 Winter Olympics]] in [[Lake Placid]], United States, which were held as [[demonstration sport]].<ref>[https://library.olympic.org/Default/digitalCollection/DigitalCollectionAttachmentDownloadHandler.ashx?documentId=159087&skipWatermark=true]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410085042/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1932/1932w.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=April 10, 2008|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> She finished fourth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500 metres event]] and fifth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1000 metres|1000 metres event]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1000-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,000 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> She also competed in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 500 metres|500 metres event]] but was eliminated in the heats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring her career she competed in several other international competitions where she was successful, including at the 1929 Middle Atlantic Senior SpeedSkating Championship for Girls.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/411903028/]</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/411903184/]</ref><ref name=archive.macleans /><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UWspDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+struggle+for+Canadian+sport&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjajMWO6svoAhVuMewKHcTOD7QQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=the%20struggle%20for%20Canadian%20sport&f=false]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackie, Geraldine}}\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of Canada]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Canadian female speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n{{Canada-speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American speed skater}}\n{{Infobox speed skater\n| name           = G\u00e9raldine Mackie\n| nickname = \u201cJerry\u201d Mackie<ref name=archive.macleans />\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| headercolor    = #d7ecff\n| country        = Canada\n| club           = \n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight \t = \n| turnedpro      = \n| retired        = \n|medaltemplates=\n\n}}\n'''G\u00e9raldine Mackie''' was a female [[Canada|Canadian]] [[speed skater]]. She lived in [[Toronto]], Canada.<ref name=archive.macleans>[https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1929/3/1/speed-is-their-game]</ref>\n\nShe competed in all the three women's [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics|speed skating events at the 1932 Winter Olympics]] in [[Lake Placid]], United States, which were held as [[demonstration sport]].<ref>[https://library.olympic.org/Default/digitalCollection/DigitalCollectionAttachmentDownloadHandler.ashx?documentId=159087&skipWatermark=true]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410085042/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1932/1932w.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=April 10, 2008|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> She finished fourth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1500 metres|1500 metres event]] and fifth in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 1000 metres|1000 metres event]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-1000-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 1,000 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> She also competed in the [[Speed skating at the 1932 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's 500 metres|500 metres event]] but was eliminated in the heats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/winter/1932/SSK/womens-500-metres.html|title=Speed Skating at the 1932 Lake Placid Winter Games: Women's 500 metres|website=Olympics at Sports-Football-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring her career she competed in several other international competitions where she was succesful, including at the 1929 Middle Atlantic Senior SpeedSkating Championship for Girls.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/411903028/]</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/411903184/]</ref><ref name=archive.macleans /><ref>[https://books.google.nl/books?id=UWspDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+struggle+for+Canadian+sport&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjajMWO6svoAhVuMewKHcTOD7QQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=the%20struggle%20for%20Canadian%20sport&f=false]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackie, Geraldine}}\n[[Category:Olympic speed skaters of Canada]]\n[[Category:Speed skaters at the 1932 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Canadian female speed skaters]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Date of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n\n{{Canada-speed-skating-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%A9raldine_Mackie"}
{"title_page": "Rank insignia of the Carabinieri", "text_new": "As the [[Arma dei Carabinieri]] is the fourth service of the [[Italian armed forces]], the '''Ranks and rank insignia of the Carabinieri''' are designed according to the military rank structure of Italy. Carabinieri personnel belongs to four different career paths, the Officer career, the Inspector career, the ''Sovrintendente'' career, and the basic Carabinieri career.\n==Ruoli Ufficiale==\nCandidates for the non-technical Officer career of the Carabinieri are recruited through the [[Military Academy of Modena]].  At the end of the two-year period, students graduate in \"Legal Sciences\" and are appointed Sottotenente. The cycle of studies continues for another three years at the Carabinieri Officer School, at the end of which the students obtain a master's degree in Law and, on a voluntary basis, also one in \"Internal and external security sciences\" (in agreement with the [[University of Rome Tor Vergata]]). Appointment to ''Tenente'' is after two years at the school.<ref>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/ufficiali \"Diventare Ufficiale.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref> \n\nNon-technical officers are also recruited by direct appointment as ''Sottotenente'' by ''Luogotenente'', under 50 years old, with a [[Master's degree]], and by all other ranks with at least five years service, under 40 years old, with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in law.<ref name=Ispettori/> <ref name=Sovrintendente/> <ref name=Carabinerie/> The directly appointed ''Sottotenente'' are trained for two years at the Carabinieri Officer School, obtaining a master's degree in Law and promotion to ''Tenente.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"25\" | NATO-code\n! align=\"left\" width=\"300\" | Rank\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Rank insignia  <ref>[http://www.carabinieri.it/arma/oggi/uniformi/distintivi-di-grado/distintivi-di-grado-da-ufficiale \"Distintivi di grado: Ufficiali.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n|-\n| OF-9||Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />Comandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-9a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-8 || Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />Vicecomandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-9b.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />''former'' Vicecomandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Generale di Corpo d'Armata ex vcg.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Generale di Corpo d'Armata || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-8.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-7 || Generale di Divsione<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Generale di Divisione con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Generale di Divisione|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-7.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Generale di Divisione<br />''Honorary rank''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Generale di Divisione a titolo onorifico.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2|OF-6|| Generale di Brigata<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Generale di Brigata con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Generale di Brigata|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-6.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4|OF-5|| Colonello<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Colonnello con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Colonello<br />''Commanding officer ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-5a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Colonello<br /> || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-5.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Colonello<br />''Honorary rank''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Colonnello a titolo onorifico.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-4|| Tenente colonello<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Tenente Colonnello con incarichi di Colonnello.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Tenente colonello<br />''Commanding officer ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-4a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Tenente colonello<br /> || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-4.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-3|| Maggiore<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Maggiore con funzione di Tenente Colonnello.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Maggiore<br />''Commanding officer ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-3a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Maggiore<br /> || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-3.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-2|| Capitano<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Capitano con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Primo Capitano || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Rank insignia of primo capitano of the Arma dei Carabinieri.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Capitano<br /> || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-2.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-1|| Tenente<br />''Commanding officer''\n  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri Tenente con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Tenente<br />''After two years at the Carabinieri Officer School   ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-1a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| Sottotenente<br />''At the Carabinieri Officer School ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OF-1b.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|OF-D|| Allievo ufficiale<br />''At the [[Military Academy of Modena]] (2 years) ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Rank insignia of allievo ufficiale of the Italian Army.svg|50px]]\n|}\n\n==Ruoli Ispettori==\nCandidates for the Inspector career are by law recruited to 70% by internal or civilian applicants with a high school diploma, to 20% from the Sovrintendente career, and to 10% from the basic Carabinieri career. The former candidates attend a three-year university-based training process at the School of Marshals and Brigadiers of the Carabinieri, graduating with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in \"Legal Sciences of Security\" at the [[University of Rome Tor Vergata]], while the latter candidates are trained for six months at the School of Marshals and Brigadiers of the Carabinieri.<ref name=Ispettori>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/ispettori \"Deveniri Ispettore.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>  <ref>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/formazione/la-scuola-marescialli-e-brigadieri \"La Scuola Marescialli e Brigadieri.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"25\" | NATO-code\n! align=\"left\" width=\"300\" | Rank\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Rank insignia <ref>[http://www.carabinieri.it/arma/oggi/uniformi/distintivi-di-grado/distintivi-di-grado-per-maresciallo \"Distintivi di grado: Marescialli.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=4|OR-9 || Luogotenente \u00abCarica Speciale\u00bb|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-Luogotenente-Carica-Speciale.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Luogetenente  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OW-5.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|  Maresciallo maggiore || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OW-4.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Maresciallo capo  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OW-3.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2|OR-8 || Maresciallo ordinario || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OW-2.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Maresciallo || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OW-1.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|n/a ||Allievo maresciallo|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Rank insignia of allievo maresciallo of Carabinieri.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Ruoli Sovrintendente==\nCandidates for the Sovrintendente career are by law recruited to 60 % from the ''Appuntato scelto'' and to 40% from the lower ranks of the basic Carabinieri career. The former candidates are trained during one month, and the latter candidates during three months, at the School of Marshals and Brigadiers of the Carabinieri.<ref name=Sovrintendente>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/sovrintendenti \"Diventare Sovrintendente.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"25\" | NATO-code\n! align=\"left\" width=\"300\" | Rank\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Rank insignia  <ref>[http://www.carabinieri.it/arma/oggi/uniformi/distintivi-di-grado/distintivi-di-grado-per-brigadiere \"Distintivi di grado: Brigadiere.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|OR-7 || Brigadiere capo \u00abQualifica Speciale\u00bb|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-9a.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Brigadiere capo|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-9b.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|OR-6||Brigadiere|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Carabinieri-OR-9c.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|OR-5|| Vicebrigadiere || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-8.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Ruoli Appuntati e Carabinieri==\nCandidates for the basic carabinieri career are by law recruited to 70 % from serving soldiers with one or four year enlistments as temporary service volunteers, and to 30 % from civilian life irrespective of previous military service.<ref>Decreto Legislativo 15 marzo 2010, n. 66. Codice dell'Ordinamento Militare.</ref> <ref>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/concorsi-pubblici/concorso-per-esami-e-titoli-per-il-reclutamento-di-3.581-allievi-carabinieri-in-ferma-quadriennale \"Concorso, per esami e titoli, per il reclutamento di 3.581 allievi carabinieri in ferma quadriennale.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref> Initial enlistment is for a period of four years, after which permanent status is achieved.<ref name=Carabinerie>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/app-e-car- \"Diventare Carabiniere.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref> Training is one year at one of five Carabinieri schools. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"25\" | NATO-code\n! align=\"left\" width=\"300\" | Rank\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Rank insignia <ref>[http://www.carabinieri.it/arma/oggi/uniformi/distintivi-di-grado/distintivi-di-grado-per-app-car- \"Distintivi di grado: Appuntati e Carabinieri.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=5|OR-4 || Appuntato scelto \u00abQualifica Speciale\u00bb|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-Appuntato-scelto-qualifica-speciale.png|50px]]\n|-\n|Appuntato scelto || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-7b.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Appuntato || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-6.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Carabiniere scelto || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-5.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|Carabiniere || style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-4.svg|50px]]\n|-\n| n/a||Allievo carabinere<br />''During the first six months at the Carabinieri school (1 year) ''|| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[File:Carabinieri-OR-4.svg|50px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Italian Army ranks]]\n* [[Italian Navy ranks]]\n* [[Italian Air Force ranks]]\n\n{{Military ranks by country}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carabinieri ranks}}\n[[Category:Carabinieri|*]]\n[[Category:Military insignia]]\n[[Category:Military ranks of Italy]]\n", "text_old": "As the [[Arma dei Carabinieri]] is the fourth service of the [[Italian armed forces]], the '''Ranks and rank insignia of the Carabinieri''' are designed according to the military rank structure of Italy. Carabinieri personnel belongs to four different career paths, the Officer career, the Inspector career, the ''Sovrintendente'' career, and the basic Carabinieri career.\n==Ruoli Ufficiale==\nCandidates for the non-technical Officer career of the Carabinieri are recruited through the [[Military Academy of Modena]].  At the end of the two-year period, students graduate in \"Legal Sciences\" and are appointed Sottotenente. The cycle of studies continues for another three years at the Carabinieri Officer School, at the end of which the students obtain a master's degree in Law and, on a voluntary basis, also one in \"Internal and external security sciences\" (in agreement with the [[University of Rome Tor Vergata]]). Appointment to ''Tenente'' is after two years at the school.<ref>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/ufficiali \"Diventare Ufficiale.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref> \n\nNon-technical officers are also recruited by direct appointment as ''Sottotenente'' by ''Luogotenente'', under 50 years old, with a [[Master's degree]], and by all other ranks with at least five years service, under 40 years old, with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in law.<ref name=Ispettori/> <ref name=Sovrintendente/> <ref name=Carabinerie/> The directly appointed ''Sottotenente'' are trained for two years at the Carabinieri Officer School, obtaining a master's degree in Law and promotion to ''Tenente.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"25\" | NATO-code\n! align=\"left\" width=\"300\" | Rank\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Rank insignia  <ref>[http://www.carabinieri.it/arma/oggi/uniformi/distintivi-di-grado/distintivi-di-grado-da-ufficiale \"Distintivi di grado: Ufficiali.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n|-\n| OF-9||Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />Comandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-9a.svg|50px]] </center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-8 || Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />Vicecomandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-9b.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Generale di Corpo d'Armata<br />''former'' Vicecomandante generale dell'Arma dei Carabinieri  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Generale di Corpo d'Armata ex vcg.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Generale di Corpo d'Armata || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-8.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-7 || Generale di Divsione<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Generale di Divisione con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Generale di Divisione|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-7.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Generale di Divisione<br />''Honorary rank''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri Generale di Divisione a titolo onorifico.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|OF-6|| Generale di Brigata<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Generale di Brigata con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Generale di Brigata|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-6.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=4|OF-5|| Colonello<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Colonnello con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Colonello<br />''Commanding officer ''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-5a.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Colonello<br /> || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-5.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Colonello<br />''Honorary rank''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri Colonnello a titolo onorifico.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-4|| Tenente colonello<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Tenente Colonnello con incarichi di Colonnello.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Tenente colonello<br />''Commanding officer ''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-4a.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Tenente colonello<br /> || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-4.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-3|| Maggiore<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Maggiore con funzione di Tenente Colonnello.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Maggiore<br />''Commanding officer ''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-3a.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Maggiore<br /> || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-3.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-2|| Capitano<br />''Serving in higher rank''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Capitano con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Primo Capitano || <center>[[File:Rank insignia of primo capitano of the Arma dei Carabinieri.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Capitano<br /> || <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-2.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|OF-1|| Tenente<br />''Commanding officer''\n  || <center>[[File:Carabinieri Tenente con incarichi al grado superiore.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Tenente<br />''After two years at the Carabinieri Officer School   ''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-1a.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n| Sottotenente<br />''At the Carabinieri Officer School ''|| <center>[[File:Carabinieri-OF-1b.svg|50px]]</center>\n|-\n|OF-D|| Allievo ufficiale<br />''At the [[Military Academy of Modena]] (2 years) ''||<center>[[File:Rank insignia of allievo ufficiale of the Italian Army.svg|50px]]</center>\n|}\n\n==Ruoli Ispettori==\nCandidates for the Inspector career are by law recruited to 70% by internal or civilian applicants with a high school diploma, to 20% from the Sovrintendente career, and to 10% from the basic Carabinieri career. The former candidates attend a three-year university-based training process at the School of Marshals and Brigadiers of the Carabinieri, graduating with a [[Bachelor's degree]] in \"Legal Sciences of Security\" at the [[University of Rome Tor Vergata]], while the latter candidates are trained for six months at the School of Marshals and Brigadiers of the Carabinieri.<ref name=Ispettori>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/reclutamento/ispettori \"Deveniri Ispettore.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>  <ref>[https://www.carabinieri.it/concorsi/area-concorsi/formazione/la-scuola-marescialli-e-brigadieri \"La Scuola Marescialli e Brigadieri.\" ''Carabinieri.''] Retrieved 2020-03-11.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgco